Feb 23 2006	Great hotel for the hard of hearing	My husband and I stayed at the Soho House recently for one night. While the hotel staff was friendly, the room was fantastic and the bar was a nice place to have a drink before venturing out to dinner, it did not make up for the absurdly excessive noise level from the surrounding night clubs. I am a native New Yorker and consider myself fairly immune to the din of the city but I have never experienced anything like this before. It started around midnight the noise from people talking outside our window waiting to get into the clubs, continued with the sound of cab horns honking ever 2 minutes, bottles clanking and the grand finally of night club personnel directing cab traffic when the club closed at 3:30am! We mentioned the noise level to the staff the next morning and they said there was nothing they could do about it as all the rooms face the street and they are surrouned by night clubs. This was supposed to be a relaxing, peaceful night away for us and turned out to be the exact opposite. Unfortunately, we will never stay here again and will not recommend it for anyone else unless you are planning to take full advantage of the nightlife in the area.	
Feb 23 2006 	What are they talking about	Having stayed at The Soho House around 15 times since it opened I cannot believe the reviews I read. Yes there are elements that could be improved, but isn't that the case with everything in life.The noise issue has been fixed with new windows, the TV's have even been fixed. The staff are super friendly and helpful and will try and accommodate you in any way possible.In regards to the roof, it isn't Soho House's fault if a TV program made their space look bigger, that program isn't real life!!On the whole, I have enjoyed every stay, even when there is a problem the staff and management have gone out of there way to make it up.I would recommend people try it our for themselves.	
Jan 30 2006	Bad but not in the ways I expected	I travel extensively and I try to stay in the best places. Money is not an issue so long as I get a good product. I was a bit worried about booking Soho House given the reviews posted here about bad service. In fact, I found all the staff wonderful. I was never asked to identify myself upon entering the club. I even brought in eight guests both days for drinks etc. which contravenes club rules, but the staff were perfectly accommodating. Indeed, the service was super-attentive for food, drinks etc. The room was also fabulous with one of the best showers ever. The BIG problem was noise. It is absolutely impossible to get to sleep before 3am due to the noise from people coming out of the Hotel Gansevoort opposite and the constant honking of taxi cab horns. It drove me to distraction. Moreover, because of the design of the rooms, with cool Bose surround sound, if you listen to TV in your room at a normal volume, next door has a booming volume level. We were woken at 8am by a guy playing TV and went to ask him to turn it down. It was amazing that it was louder in our room than his. So all in all, no matter how gorgeous a room and how wonderful the staff, if you don't get a good night's sleep -what's the point?!	
Jan 5 2006	Beautiful rooms but terrible service	My husband and I are members of this private club and have stayed here quite often, most recently in Summer, 2005. We live in the neighborhood and book for special occassions. I do have to agree that even though we have been members for two years running, and the rooms and amenities are the best I have seen anywhere, the staff is terrible. The service has always been horrible and the one attentive and competent staff member they had just moved to Germany. You can sit in the club for an hour without anyone offering you so much as a drink or a menu. I have had other issues with the staff. A female manager was so rude to me one time she almost had me in tears. Fortunately, she has now been move to the back of the house and away from dealing with the public. There is also a guy who works the main door and he should be slapped (as one of the other reviews stated) as every time I enter, he has such attitude. Also, the food stinks and drinks are overpriced.If you want an absolutely beautiful room and not feel like you are staying in an overpriced closet (most upscale NYC rooms are pricey, AND the size of a closet) then this is the place to be, if you don't mind looking elsewhere for food, courtesy, and service. The prices have creeped up (I can't say gradually) over two years, mainly due to the popularity of the place and the limited quantity of rooms (and also the stupid place was featured in an episode of &quot;Sex in The City&quot;, and the only way to get in is to be a member or rent a room, so every yahoo wants a part of it.)If they weren't so busy expanding to L.A., etc. Maybe Mark (The G.M.) would be present to pay attention to the behavior of his staff... but alas, he's not around much anymore, and so has to rely on the 'he said/she said' of staff vs. guests/members to resolve disputes. Unfortunately, at Soho House, the 'customer' is not always right (actually, rarely is.)	
Nov 12 2005	Beautiful Hotel	Myself and my partner stayed at this hotel last year. I have to say it really is beautiful, gorgeous interior design, fab spa with the best pedicure ever, spacious rooms with a generous supply of bath and hair products from the Cowshed range. The location is uber cool with fantastic restaurants such as the Spice Market and Pastis and boutiques if you feel like sending your credit card into meltdown.My only complaints are that the bar was closed one evening for a 'staff party' of all things so food and drinks were not being served. Also as numerous people have commented that the staff do not make an effort to get to at least recognise your face and you are greated every time you walk into the lobby with &quot;yes can i help you&quot; you must show you card every time you enter although they do not tell you this upon arrival.The food is also slightly overpriced at $60 for 2 english breakfasts with coffee and juice, although the quality is good you can get a fab breakfast at Pastis for $25. In the bar try the divine Lycee MartiniOverall if you can put the frosty service to the back of your mind this is the place to stay in New York	
Oct 10 2005	Expensive...but mainly worth it!	There seems to be some really varied reviews about the Soho House and I would like to share my total experience...I would have to agree with the previous review, the rooms are quite noisy. This is because the Soho House is in the trendy Meat Packing district of New York and from 11pm the cab drivers descend upon the area to pick up the revellers.I would also have to agree that the roof area is smaller than I expected, but understand it is about to undergo some work, so it may improve, but it really isn't that bad.The bedrooms are absolutely fabulous - huge beds and a fantastic bath at the end of the bed. The shower has an in-built steam-room facility - pure luxury. The TV in our room was fine, as was the quality of the sound.I expressed my concern over the outside noise to the staff after the first night. They could not have been more helpful. They also did everything they could to recommend and get us into some of the best restaurants. We decided very late on Saturday that we wanted to eat at the very popular Blue Water Grill. The staff really went out of their way for us and got us a table at a fully booked restaurant. The room service staff were extremely curtious and possibly some of the politest I have ever come across. The door staff would always flag a cab for us without us even asking.A tip for future travellers - this is a private members club and as such many people come through the small front desk - many people no doubt trying to 'blag' their way in. The staff seem to change quite regularly, so show the staff your room key when you walk through the front door - then they know who you are (it's a shame they don't tell you this themselves...). If you don't mind a bit of noise and want to stay in a fabulous room at a 'hotel' in a very trendy area of NY that has a pool on the roof and you don't mind spending some serious cash - you will enjoy the Soho House!	
Oct 6 2005	Pity about the staff	Unfortunately the gentleman from Paris is correct. I'll come back to this in a moment. In terms of background we have stayed at many 5* hotels throughout the world. The Soho House was certainly one of the most expensive, but I do feel well qualified to comment on luxury hotels.The location is good with many boutiques, bars and restaurants nearby. Shortish walk from the subway. A little noisy at night. The room itself was very good and did not dissapoint. Huge (altough at 750 USD + tax it should be) and very styllish. Excellent bathroom area with generous freebie products. A couple of small issues. It is all very well having flat screen TVs and surround sound, but it was very difficult (and I have a complex home cinema system and know a bit about these things) to get any sound from the TV, and when I did manage there was terrible hissing from the speakers. I also felt the living area and bedroom were the wrong way round, with the bedroom being beside the window, and the living area being sandwiched between bedroom and bathroom. All in all these are minor points however.The rooftop pool area is smaller than suggested by the Sex and the City episode. Comfortable chairs and loungers were sometimes at a premium.My main objection by far was the horrible and snooty staff. Who do they think they are? The reception staff were bad enough - barely tolerable - but the staff on the pooltop area needed a good slapping.They were so bad that my wife and I felt reluctant to explore the other public areas of the hotel.The Hotel Gansevoort is across the street and appeared very styllish also. Better rooftop pool. Cannot comment on the staff, but they would have to try hard to be more unfriendly that at Soho House.	
May 4 2005	mostly very nice	we just got back from four wonderful days in new york. the soho house is overall a good experience but it is not without it's flaws.  when we first arrived they were very welcoming, showed us around the room in detail, offered to reserve tables at exclusive restaurants, bars and clubs and generally said use this place like your own home The room we had was lovely, large for new york standards with a funky industrial loft feel. lots of freebees, giant plasma screen, fantastic shower and tub but abit shabby round the edges (big stains around the bath, dirty windows) but the good definitely outshone the bad by a mile.there is a beautiful roof top pool (very warm) with terrific views over the meatpackers district, a funky club and it is in a fantastic location. very sex-in-the city...but, considering the $550 per night price tag we expected a little more. like the french guy who wrote the first review, we too were a little offended at the slightly snooty reception staff who failed to recognise us on a number of occasions, asking 'can we help' in a dont-really-mean-it way on our arrival back at the hotel. whilst in the middle of sorting out a reservation for us a woman-of-the-moment celebrity who was also staying there returned and we were dropped like a hot potato and never really picked up again! now, we may not be A list celebrities but we dont scrub up too bad and certainly dont look out of place in an upmarket hotel. We just felt like the staff were tolerating us rather than welcoming us and for that price we expected more. maybe the problem is that this place lacks identity in terms of whether it is a hotel or a private members club.they failed to inform us before our arrival that their famous spa was closed but offered no reduction and we had to discover the bar / club / restaurant ourselves. we got the feeling they hoped we wouldnt find it!so on the whole, a good experience glad we have been but would probably chose to stay somewhere where our dollar was alittle more appreciated (I suspect they feel the same too!)	
Dec 11 2004	If this place isn't your cup of tea you need to switch to coffee.	I cannot imagine what that fella from Paris went through to give it a 2 out of 5. Someone was rude at the desk? Sure, that should factor into the voting scale, but to give this hotel a 2 out of 5 is just plain idiotic. The place is GORGEOUS. The guests can be pompous, O.K., but I don't go places to hang out with the other guests, so what the hell do I care? The food was excellent. The rooms were damn near perfect. The service was top notch. The roof is... yes, amazing. If you don't enjoy this place, you need to look long and hard in the mirror and ask yourself how you became so bitter in life. Everything said, however, assumes that you have a limitless budget. Because it is expensive. Very expensive. But if you can swing it, it's worth every single hundred dollar bill.	
